equence of environmental factors: of the influence of climate, soils and hydrology, and of the patterns of contact and communication engendered by natural topography. He also suggests that such environmental influences have been neglected over recent decades by generations of scholars who are embedded in an urban culture and largely divorced from the natural world; and that an appreciation of the fundamental role of physical geography in shaping human affairs can throw much new light on a number of important debates about early medieval society. The book will be essential reading for all those interestedin the character of the Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian settlements, in early medieval social and territorial organization, and in the origins of the England's medieval landscapes. Tom Williamson is Professor of LandscapeHistory, University of East Anglia; he has written widely on landscape archaeology, agricultural history, and the history of landscape design.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman geographyzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLand settlement patternszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLandscape assessmentzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon Period.  aAnglo-Saxon period.  aEarly Medieval Society.  aEarly medieval England.  aEngland.  aField Systems.  aGeographical Features.  aLandscape.  aNatural Environment.  aPhysical Geography.  aRegional Variations.  aSettlement Patterns.  aSocial Structures.  aenvironment.  afield systems.  ageographical features.  ahistorical analysis.  alandscape.  aphysical geography.  asettlement patterns.  asocial structures.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204053840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782040538423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/documen